LASSA FEVER - USA (NEW JERSEY): ex LIBERIA
*****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1] Date: Mon 25 May 2015
Source: NJ [edited]
http://www.nj.com/healthfit/index.ssf/2015/05/patient_in_nj_dies_of_lassa_fever_says_cdc.html


A U.S. traveler who recently returned from West Africa has died in a New Jersey hospital of Lassa Fever, a viral hemorrhagic fever rarely seen in the United States, the U.S. Centers for Disease Control and Prevention announced late Monday night [25 May 2015].

The unidentified traveler landed at John F. Kennedy International Airport [New York, NY] 17 May [2015], flying from Liberia via Morocco. He had no fever or symptoms during the flight, nor when he was screened at the airport upon arrival.

The next day, however, he went to an unnamed hospital in New Jersey complaining of a sore throat, fever and fatigue. When asked about his recent travel history -- a common question in wake of ongoing fears about the Ebola virus -- he did not reveal his recent visit to Liberia, according to the CDC.

He was treated and released, but returned to the hospital last Thursday, 21 May [2015], because his symptoms had worsened. He was transferred to an unnamed facility designed to treat viral hemorrhagic fevers and specimens were submitted to the CDC for testing.

The test results, available Monday morning [25 May 2015], confirmed Lassa Fever but were negative for Ebola and other viruses.

The patient died Monday evening, according to the CDC. Throughout his treatment he was in "appropriate isolation."

This is just the 6th case of Lassa [fever] in the United States since the virus was discovered in Nigeria in 1969. The last case here was in Minnesota, in 2014. There has never been a person-to-person transmission of the disease in the United States, according to the CDC.

While Lassa fever and Ebola originate in roughly the same part of West Africa, they vary greatly in how contagious they are and how deadly. Ebola can be spread from person to person via contaminated bodily fluids and has a fatality rate approaching 70 percent, according to the CDC.

Lassa, however, has a fatality rate of 1 percent. The illness can be quite severe in about 20 percent of patients, and it routinely kills about 5000 West Africans every year. The virus is named for the locale where it was first located. It is a zoonotic virus -- meaning it is spread by animals. It is most often spread to people when they come in contact with rat droppings.

"In rare cases it can be transmitted from person to person through direct contact with a sick person's blood or bodily fluids, through mucous membranes, or through sexual contact," the CDC indicated in its announcement Monday night. "The virus is not transmitted through casual contact, and patients are not believed to be infectious before the onset of symptoms."

CDC officials are now working with local health workers to compile a list of anyone who may have had close contact with the deceased. They will be monitored for 21 days to see if they develop any symptoms.

[Byline: Kathleen O'Brien]

