[Lassa fever virus (LFV) is endemic in West Africa, including Liberia, and multi-mammate mice (_Mastomys_ spp.) are the rodent hosts. Lassa fever cases have been reported sporadically in Liberia. The Lassa fever belt in Liberia primarily occupies Lofa, Bong and Nimba Counties across the northern tier of counties bordering Guinea. The last outbreak in Liberia posted on ProMED-mail (archive no. 20140328.2363217) was in 2014, citing a report from the CDC. On that occasion, the Ministry of Health (MOH) of Liberia notified WHO of an outbreak of Lassa fever in a UN Mission in Liberia Kakata camp, Margibi County. A total of 14 cases including 1 death were reported from 27 Feb 2014 to 10 Mar 2014. The last case of Lassa fever contracted in Liberia with death occurring in the USA, coincidentally also in New Jersey, was in 2004. The current case, reported above, illustrates the importance of obtaining an accurate travel history. Apparently, in this case above, the patient failed to report that he had been in Liberia, which likely delayed his hospitalization and treatment.

The virus is a member of the family _Arenaviridae_ and causes acute hemorrhagic fever. It is transmitted to humans from contact with food or household items contaminated with excreta of the reservoir rodent host. In the absence of adequate infection control measures, person-to-person virus transmission can occur in houses or in hospital environments, or in laboratories testing samples from patients. There is no preventative vaccine or treatment, though the antiviral drug ribavirin has been used successfully in Lassa fever patients

Images of _Mastomys_ mice can be seen at http://www.ispot.org.za/node/255877. - Mod.TY

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3386913,54.]
